What does the "S" in SOLID stand for, and what does it encourage?
a) Single Responsibility Principle - Encourages a class to have only one reason to change. X
b) Substitution Principle - Encourages using subtypes interchangeably.
c) Single Instance Principle - Encourages using a single instance of a class.

Which SOLID principle states that a class should have only one reason to change?
a) Single Responsibility Principle X
b) Open-Closed Principle
c) Liskov Substitution Principle

The "O" in SOLID stands for what?
a) Open-Closed Principle - open for new stuff (extension) closed for modification (existing stuff)
b) Open Source Principle
c) Object-Oriented Principle

Which SOLID principle suggests that software entities should be open for extension but closed for modification?
a) Single Responsibility Principle
b) Open-Closed Principle X
c) Interface Segregation Principle

Which SOLID principle is concerned with ensuring that subclasses can be substituted for their base classes without affecting
 the correctness of the program?
a) Liskov Substitution Principle
b) Dependency Inversion Principle
c) Interface Segregation Principle

What does the "I" in SOLID stand for, and what does it advocate?
a) Immutable Principle - Advocates making objects immutable.
b) Interface Segregation Principle - Advocates splitting large interfaces into smaller, specific ones.
c) Inheritance Principle - Advocates using inheritance to achieve code reusability.

Which SOLID principle recommends that high-level modules should not depend on low-level modules but both
 should depend on abstractions?
a) Interface Segregation Principle
b) Dependency Inversion Principle
c) Liskov Substitution Principle
